      "source": [
        "# 1. Algorithms  (no science without) "
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cScY1HbXXt7O"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "In science we compute. When we compute we perform a sequence of well-defined instructions. Such sequences we call [algorithms](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm). Algorithms can be expressed in flowcharts and are conceptually known since the beginning of computation (antiquity). \n",
        "\n",
        "An example\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VkPcaGwmXztf"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "![440px-Euclid_flowchart.svg.png](data:image/png;base64,)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "j4fR6DctFv8Y"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "- Try this algorithm with for example A=10 and B=5\n",
        "- Reproducibility is only reliably achievable with algorithms\n",
        "\n",
        "Are you an algorithm? Please vote [here](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSc1U9FGUqwizHwXZSf1dtGHwaGqyxjQuRxnhHYFPy1VUtrL4g/viewform?usp=sf_link) !\n",
        "\n",
        "Can you think of a simple algorithm you learned in school?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "zLGSUiDIGW3k"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# 2. Languages"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "M0iAVtE9S3Ee"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "To implement algorithms we need language. Normally one uses (formal) programming languages (code) and not natural languages. Some prominent examples:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Machine Code\n",
        "- Assembly (1947)\n",
        "- Fortran, COBOL, LISP ... (1950s)\n",
        "- BASIC .. (1960s)\n",
        "- Pascal, C (1970s) \n",
        "- C++ (1980s)\n",
        "- Python, R (1990s)\n",
        "- Java, PHP, ... (1990s)\n",
        "- Julia (2010s)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "40Gl-g_ETyh5"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "One normally distinguish between scripting languages, like bash or python, and non-scripting languages like C/C++ and Fortran. Scripts can be executed immediately statement by statement during runtime and do not require compilation, i.e. the explicit translation step into machine code.  "
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3I5V9mykRcry"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "3+2"
      ],

          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

        "id": "ZPt0EEwcUgSx",

      },

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# 3. Computers"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Z98316hcUiZ7"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Algorithms formulated in a language can be performed. The performers are normally called computers.\n",
        "\n",
        "- The first computers were humans, often women (\"kilo-girls\", \"girls-hours\")\n",
        "- The first non-human computers were mechanical\n",
        "- Then the semi-conductor (transistor) computers came (1960s)\n",
        "- Then the internet and therfore distributed computing came\n",
        "- Then the personal computers came (1970/80s)\n",
        "- Then the mouse came \n",
        "- Then www came (1989 -)\n",
        "- Then cloud computing came (google, azure, amazon, alibaba ...) (2000s)\n",
        "- Then IoT and Dataism came\n",
        "- Then comes what ?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9i7GOIGPUvpU"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "![computer_wide.jpeg](data:image/jpeg;base64,)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Rnx-yRrsTjD3"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**From now on we will consider our research as algorithms, implement it in the python language and let computers do the work! This way we will become more efficient, more knowledgable and more reproducible - in short more ethical.**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "f5GDkRuNWOmA"
      }
    },

        "# 4. Jupyter Notebooks"

      "metadata": {

      },
      "source": [
        "(Use some minutes to go through this notebook on colab)\n",
        "\n",
        "[Jupyter notebooks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Project_Jupyter) \n",
        "* is a browser based graphical interface\n",
        "* can execute Python (and other programming language) statements\n",
        "* can handle formatted text, maths equations (LaTeX)\n",
        "* can contain static or dynamic visualisations\n",
        "* is this\n",
        "\n",
        "Over the last years Jupyter notebooks have become popular for\n",
        "* data science and data analysis\n",
        "* lab work\n",
        "* teaching and presenting\n",
        "* publication of reproducible research\n",
        "* development of code\n",
        "\n",
        "Jupyter notebooks are not always the right tool. It is not optimal for\n",
        "* programming large software codes\n",
        "* running in production\n",
        "* automatisation \n",
        "* etc\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },

        "id": "gqRROYrSmxa3"
      },
      "source": [
        "### The Filename Extension and the Jupyter Name\n",
        "\n",
        "* The filename extension .ipynb stands for interactive python notebook\n",
        "* Jupyter is and abreviation for the three popular data science languages Julia, Python and R."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "IrRoMikunfhH"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Colab versus other ways of running Jupyter Notebooks\n",
        "\n",
        "* [Colab](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colab) is a service offered by google and runs Jupyter notebooks. It is interfaced with google login, drive etc which makes it nice for sharing and coworking in the same environment. \n",
        "* You can install and run notebooks locally on your laptop. To do so you need to install it. It is recommended to install via the Anaconda platform.\n",
        "* There are also other cloud platforms for running Jupyter notebooks\n",
        "\n",
        "In this course we use colab and there is no need for you to install anything."
      ]
